'''Steve Hely''' is an [[United States|American]] [[writer]].

Hely has written for the television shows ''[[Late Show with David Letterman]]'' (receiving an [[Emmy]] nomination for Outstanding Writing for a Variety or Comedy Show), ''[[Last Call with Carson Daly]]'', where he also served as an [[associate producer]], ''[[American Dad]]'', ''[[30 Rock]]'', and ''[[The Office (U.S. TV series)|The Office]]''.<ref name="macmillan.com"/><ref>[http://www.imdb.com/name/nm1259707/ imbd]</ref>

Hely has also authored or co-authored two books. ''The Ridiculous Race'', written with Vali Chandrasekaran and published in 2008 by [[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan]], chronicled a real-life race around the world between Hely and Chandrasekaran. Each set off from [[Los Angeles]] in opposite directions, with only one rule: "No airplanes."<ref name="macmillan.com"/> In 2009, [[Grove/Atlantic]] published Hely's [[debut novel]], ''How I Became A Famous Novelist''.<ref>[http://www.groveatlantic.com/grove/bin/wc.dll?GroveProc~search~steve%20hely GroveAtlantic]</ref> Hely subsequently won the 2010 [[Thurber Prize for American Humor]] for the novel.<ref>[http://www.thurberhouse.org/2010-thurber-prize-for-american-humor.html Thurber House]</ref>

Hely attended the [[Roxbury Latin School]] and [[Harvard University]], where he received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree. While at Harvard, Hely served two terms as president of the ''[[Harvard Lampoon]]''.<ref name="macmillan.com">[http://us.macmillan.com/theridiculousrace macmillan.com]</ref>

==Television appearances==

Hely has appeared onscreen in select episodes of ''[[30 Rock]]'' and [[The Office (U.S. TV series)|''The Office'']]. He appeared as a poster-collecting bachelor named Jerem in the ''30 Rock'' episode "[[Lee Marvin vs. Derek Jeter]]". Additionally, he appeared as a flautist and shirtless bohemian in ''The Office'' episode "[[Gettysburg (The Office)|Gettysburg]]".

